Good. No existing config file infrastructure or `dirs` crate usage. Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me design the full implementation plan.

Here is the detailed implementation plan for improving the Arcan CLI UX with persistent configuration and agent context.

---

## Implementation Plan: Arcan CLI Persistent Configuration

### 1. Overview

The plan introduces a two-layer configuration system: a **TOML config file** for CLI bootstrap settings (Layer 1), and **Lago-backed SessionManifest propagation** for agent context (Layer 2). It adds `--provider` and `--model` as global CLI flags, introduces `arcan config`, `arcan status`, and `arcan stop` subcommands, and ensures full backward compatibility with the existing environment-variable workflow.

---

### 2. Config File Format and Loading

**File:** NEW `arcan/crates/arcan/src/config.rs`

The config file uses TOML for simplicity and fast parsing. Two locations are searched with project-local taking precedence over global:

1. **Project-local:** `.arcan/config.toml` (relative to CWD, resolved via `data_dir`)
2. **Global:** `~/.config/arcan/config.toml` (using the `dirs` crate for cross-platform `config_dir()`)

**Struct definition:**

```rust
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::path::{Path, PathBuf};

/// Top-level persistent configuration.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[serde(default)]
pub struct ArcanConfig {
    pub defaults: DefaultsConfig,
    #[serde(default)]
    pub providers: HashMap<String, ProviderConfig>,
    #[serde(default)]
    pub agent: AgentConfig,
}

/// Default provider/model/port settings.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[serde(default)]
pub struct DefaultsConfig {
    pub provider: Option<String>,
    pub model: Option<String>,
    pub port: Option<u16>,
    pub data_dir: Option<PathBuf>,
    pub session: Option<String>,
}

impl Default for DefaultsConfig {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self {
            provider: None,
            model: None,
            port: None,
            data_dir: None,
            session: None,
        }
    }
}

/// Per-provider configuration (non-secret settings only).
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[serde(default)]
pub struct ProviderConfig {
    pub model: Option<String>,
    pub base_url: Option<String>,
    pub max_tokens: Option<u32>,
    pub enable_streaming: Option<bool>,
}

/// Agent behavior configuration.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[serde(default)]
pub struct AgentConfig {
    pub max_iterations: Option<u32>,
    pub approval_timeout: Option<u64>,
}

impl Default for AgentConfig {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self {
            max_iterations: None,
            approval_timeout: None,
        }
    }
}
```

**Loading logic:**

```rust
impl ArcanConfig {
    /// Load config from project-local and global locations, merging them.
    /// Project-local settings override global settings.
    pub fn load(data_dir: &Path) -> Self {
        let local_path = data_dir.join("config.toml");
        let global_path = Self::global_config_path();

        let global = global_path.and_then(|p| Self::load_from_file(&p));
        let local = Self::load_from_file(&local_path);

        match (global, local) {
            (Some(g), Some(l)) => g.merge(l),
            (None, Some(l)) => l,
            (Some(g), None) => g,
            (None, None) => Self::default(),
        }
    }

    fn global_config_path() -> Option<PathBuf> {
        dirs::config_dir().map(|d| d.join("arcan").join("config.toml"))
    }

    fn load_from_file(path: &Path) -> Option<Self> {
        let content = std::fs::read_to_string(path).ok()?;
        toml::from_str(&content).ok()
    }

    /// Merge: `other` overrides `self` for any non-None fields.
    fn merge(mut self, other: Self) -> Self {
        // defaults
        if other.defaults.provider.is_some() { self.defaults.provider = other.defaults.provider; }
        if other.defaults.model.is_some() { self.defaults.model = other.defaults.model; }
        if other.defaults.port.is_some() { self.defaults.port = other.defaults.port; }
        if other.defaults.data_dir.is_some() { self.defaults.data_dir = other.defaults.data_dir; }
        if other.defaults.session.is_some() { self.defaults.session = other.defaults.session; }
        // providers: deep merge
        for (name, config) in other.providers {
            let entry = self.providers.entry(name).or_default();
            if config.model.is_some() { entry.model = config.model; }
            if config.base_url.is_some() { entry.base_url = config.base_url; }
            if config.max_tokens.is_some() { entry.max_tokens = config.max_tokens; }
            if config.enable_streaming.is_some() { entry.enable_streaming = config.enable_streaming; }
        }
        // agent
        if other.agent.max_iterations.is_some() { self.agent.max_iterations = other.agent.max_iterations; }
        if other.agent.approval_timeout.is_some() { self.agent.approval_timeout = other.agent.approval_timeout; }
        self
    }

    /// Write config to the project-local config file.
    pub fn save_local(&self, data_dir: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
        std::fs::create_dir_all(data_dir)?;
        let content = toml::to_string_pretty(self)?;
        std::fs::write(data_dir.join("config.toml"), content)?;
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

**Key design decisions:**
- All fields are `Option<T>` to support partial configs and merging
- No secrets (API keys) in config files -- they stay in env vars
- `toml` crate is fast, pure Rust, zero network calls
- The `dirs` crate provides cross-platform `~/.config/` resolution

---

### 3. CLI Flag Additions

**File:** `arcan/crates/arcan/src/main.rs`

Add `--provider` and `--model` as **global** flags on the `Cli` struct:

```rust
#[derive(Parser)]
#[command(
    name = "arcan",
    about = "Arcan agent runtime with streaming and tool execution"
)]
struct Cli {
    #[command(subcommand)]
    command: Option<Command>,

    /// Data directory for journal and blob storage
    #[arg(long, default_value = ".arcan", global = true)]
    data_dir: PathBuf,

    /// HTTP listen port
    #[arg(long, global = true)]
    port: Option<u16>,  // Changed from default_value_t = 3000 to Option

    /// LLM provider (anthropic, openai, ollama, mock)
    #[arg(long, global = true)]
    provider: Option<String>,

    /// LLM model name
    #[arg(long, global = true)]
    model: Option<String>,
}
```

Note: `port` changes from a `u16` with default to `Option<u16>` so the config file default can fill in.

---

### 4. Precedence Chain

The resolution order (lowest to highest priority):

```
hardcoded defaults --> global config file --> project-local config file --> env vars --> CLI flags
```

This is implemented via a `ResolvedConfig` struct that applies each layer in order:

```rust
/// Fully resolved configuration with all layers applied.
pub struct ResolvedConfig {
    pub provider: String,
    pub model: Option<String>,  // None = let provider choose default
    pub port: u16,
    pub data_dir: PathBuf,
    pub max_iterations: u32,
    pub approval_timeout: u64,
    pub provider_config: Option<ProviderConfig>,
}

impl ResolvedConfig {
    pub fn resolve(cli: &Cli, file_config: &ArcanConfig) -> Self {
        // 1. Start with hardcoded defaults
        let mut provider = String::new(); // empty = auto-detect
        let mut model: Option<String> = None;
        let mut port: u16 = 3000;
        let mut max_iterations: u32 = 10;
        let mut approval_timeout: u64 = 300;

        // 2. Apply file config
        if let Some(p) = &file_config.defaults.provider { provider = p.clone(); }
        if let Some(m) = &file_config.defaults.model { model = Some(m.clone()); }
        if let Some(p) = file_config.defaults.port { port = p; }
        if let Some(i) = file_config.agent.max_iterations { max_iterations = i; }
        if let Some(t) = file_config.agent.approval_timeout { approval_timeout = t; }

        // 3. Apply env vars
        if let Ok(p) = std::env::var("ARCAN_PROVIDER") { if !p.is_empty() { provider = p; } }
        if let Ok(m) = std::env::var("ARCAN_MODEL") { model = Some(m); }
        if let Ok(p) = std::env::var("ARCAN_PORT") { if let Ok(p) = p.parse() { port = p; } }

        // 4. Apply CLI flags (highest priority)
        if let Some(p) = &cli.provider { provider = p.clone(); }
        if let Some(m) = &cli.model { model = Some(m.clone()); }
        if let Some(p) = cli.port { port = p; }

        // Resolve provider-specific config from file
        let provider_config = if !provider.is_empty() {
            file_config.providers.get(&provider).cloned()
        } else {
            None
        };

        Self { provider, model, port, data_dir: cli.data_dir.clone(), max_iterations, approval_timeout, provider_config }
    }
}
```

---

### 5. `arcan config` Subcommand

Add to the `Command` enum in `main.rs`:

```rust
#[derive(Subcommand)]
enum Command {
    Serve { /* existing */ },
    Chat { /* existing */ },
    Run { /* existing */ },
    /// Manage persistent configuration
    Config {
        #[command(subcommand)]
        action: ConfigAction,
    },
    /// Show daemon and runtime status
    Status,
    /// Stop the running daemon
    Stop,
}

#[derive(Subcommand)]
enum ConfigAction {
    /// Set a config value (e.g., `arcan config set provider ollama`)
    Set { key: String, value: String },
    /// Get a config value
    Get { key: String },
    /// List all config values
    List,
    /// Show the resolved config file path
    Path,
    /// Initialize a default config file
    Init,
}
```

**Implementation** in a new function `run_config()`:

- `set`: Loads existing config (or default), sets the key, writes back via `save_local()`
- `get`: Loads config, prints the value for the dotted key
- `list`: Loads config, prints the full TOML
- `path`: Prints the resolved path of the active config file
- `init`: Creates `.arcan/config.toml` with documented defaults

The key mapping uses dot notation:
- `provider` -> `defaults.provider`
- `model` -> `defaults.model`
- `port` -> `defaults.port`
- `providers.ollama.base_url` -> `providers.ollama.base_url`
- `agent.max_iterations` -> `agent.max_iterations`

For simplicity, the top-level keys (`provider`, `model`, `port`) are shortcuts into `defaults.*`.

---

### 6. `arcan status` and `arcan stop` Subcommands

**`arcan status`:**

```rust
async fn run_status(data_dir: &Path, port: u16, config: &ArcanConfig) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    // 1. Print config summary
    println!("Configuration:");
    println!("  Provider: {}", resolved.provider.as_deref().unwrap_or("(auto-detect)"));
    println!("  Model:    {}", resolved.model.as_deref().unwrap_or("(provider default)"));
    println!("  Port:     {}", resolved.port);
    println!("  Data dir: {}", data_dir.display());

    // 2. Check daemon status
    let base_url = format!("http://127.0.0.1:{port}");
    if is_daemon_healthy(&base_url).await {
        println!("\nDaemon: running on {base_url}");
        // Optionally fetch /health for uptime info

        // 3. Show active session
        if let Some(session) = resolve_session_via_api(&base_url).await {
            println!("  Session:  {session}");
        }
    } else {
        println!("\nDaemon: not running");
        if let Some(pid) = check_existing_pid(data_dir) {
            println!("  Stale PID: {pid}");
        }
    }
    Ok(())
}
