async fn run_stop(data_dir: &Path, port: u16) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let pid_path = data_dir.join("daemon.pid");
    let raw = std::fs::read_to_string(&pid_path)
        .map_err(|_| anyhow::anyhow!("No daemon.pid found — daemon may not be running"))?;
    let pid: u32 = raw.trim().parse()?;

    #[cfg(unix)]
    {
        // Send SIGTERM for graceful shutdown
        let status = std::process::Command::new("kill")
            .args([&pid.to_string()])
            .status()?;
        if status.success() {
            println!("Sent SIGTERM to daemon (PID {pid})");
            // Poll until process is gone or timeout
            for _ in 0..30 {
                tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(200)).await;
                if !is_process_alive(pid) {
                    println!("Daemon stopped.");
                    let _ = std::fs::remove_file(&pid_path);
                    return Ok(());
                }
            }
            println!("Daemon still running after 6s — you may need to kill -9 {pid}");
        }
    }
    Ok(())
}
```

---

### 7. Config Feeding into SessionManifest for Agent Context

This is the bridge between Layer 1 (TOML file) and Layer 2 (Lago-backed persistence).

**Where it connects:** When the CLI client creates or attaches to a session via `POST /sessions`, it can pass `model_routing` in the request body. Currently in `cli_run.rs`, the session is created with:

```rust
client.post(format!("{base_url}/sessions"))
    .json(&serde_json::json!({ "session_id": session_id }))
    .send().await?;
```

**Change:** Pass the resolved provider/model config into the session creation:

```rust
// In cli_run.rs or a helper
let model_routing = if let Some(model) = &resolved.model {
    Some(serde_json::json!({
        "primary_model": model,
        "fallback_models": [],
        "temperature": 0.2
    }))
} else {
    None
};

let mut body = serde_json::json!({ "session_id": session_id });
if let Some(routing) = model_routing {
    body["model_routing"] = routing;
}

client.post(format!("{base_url}/sessions"))
    .json(&body)
    .send().await?;
```

The `CreateSessionRequest` in `canonical.rs` already accepts optional `model_routing`, so no server-side changes are needed for this path.

**Provider selection on the daemon side** requires a separate mechanism: the daemon's `run_serve()` function must read the resolved config to select the provider. Currently it reads env vars directly. The change is to pass `ResolvedConfig` into `run_serve()` and use it to build provider configs.

In `run_serve()`, the provider construction changes from:

```rust
let provider_name = std::env::var("ARCAN_PROVIDER").unwrap_or_default();
```

To:

```rust
let provider_name = &resolved.provider;
// Use resolved.model and resolved.provider_config to override env defaults
```

For the specific provider configs (AnthropicConfig, OpenAiConfig), add `from_resolved()` constructors that accept the `ResolvedConfig` and fall back to env vars only for secrets:

```rust
impl AnthropicConfig {
    pub fn from_resolved(resolved: &ResolvedConfig) -> Result<Self, CoreError> {
        let api_key = std::env::var("ANTHROPIC_API_KEY").map_err(|_| {
            CoreError::Provider("ANTHROPIC_API_KEY environment variable not set".to_string())
        })?;
        let model = resolved.model.clone()
            .or_else(|| resolved.provider_config.as_ref()?.model.clone())
            .or_else(|| std::env::var("ANTHROPIC_MODEL").ok())
            .unwrap_or_else(|| "claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929".to_string());
        let base_url = resolved.provider_config.as_ref()
            .and_then(|c| c.base_url.clone())
            .or_else(|| std::env::var("ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL").ok())
            .unwrap_or_else(|| "https://api.anthropic.com".to_string());
        let max_tokens = resolved.provider_config.as_ref()
            .and_then(|c| c.max_tokens)
            .or_else(|| std::env::var("ANTHROPIC_MAX_TOKENS").ok()?.parse().ok())
            .unwrap_or(4096);
        Ok(Self { api_key, model, max_tokens, base_url })
    }
}
```

Similarly for `OpenAiConfig`:

```rust
impl OpenAiConfig {
    pub fn ollama_from_resolved(resolved: &ResolvedConfig) -> Result<Self, CoreError> {
        let model = resolved.model.clone()
            .or_else(|| resolved.provider_config.as_ref()?.model.clone())
            .or_else(|| std::env::var("OLLAMA_MODEL").ok())
            .unwrap_or_else(|| "llama3.2".to_string());
        let base_url = resolved.provider_config.as_ref()
            .and_then(|c| c.base_url.clone())
            .or_else(|| std::env::var("OLLAMA_BASE_URL").ok())
            .unwrap_or_else(|| "http://localhost:11434".to_string());
        let enable_streaming = resolved.provider_config.as_ref()
            .and_then(|c| c.enable_streaming)
            .unwrap_or(true);
        // ...
        Ok(Self { api_key: String::new(), model, max_tokens, base_url, provider_name: "ollama".to_string(), enable_streaming })
    }
}
```

**Critical constraint**: The daemon spawned by `ensure_daemon()` inherits the parent process's environment variables, so env-var-based secrets propagate naturally. The config file is on disk and the daemon re-reads it on startup. However, the `--provider` and `--model` CLI flags are NOT passed to the spawned daemon today. The daemon spawn in `daemon.rs` currently only passes `--port` and `--data-dir`. This must be extended:

```rust
let mut args = vec![
    "serve".to_string(),
    "--port".to_string(), port.to_string(),
    "--data-dir".to_string(), data_dir.to_string_lossy().to_string(),
];
if let Some(provider) = &resolved.provider {
    if !provider.is_empty() {
        args.extend(["--provider".to_string(), provider.clone()]);
    }
}
if let Some(model) = &resolved.model {
    args.extend(["--model".to_string(), model.clone()]);
}
```

Alternatively (and more cleanly), the daemon always reads the config file itself, so only the TOML file needs to be written before daemon spawn. But CLI flag overrides must be forwarded since they take priority. The cleanest approach is to forward `--provider` and `--model` to the daemon subprocess when they are explicitly set by the user.

